eavy Cruisers (HC)%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c The only thing HCs cannot hurt is a Death Star. HCs are handy against%0a%3c the big stuff, but I don't use them in main fleet formations unless I'm%0a%3c attacking something with BBs or higher. HCs are fairly efficient, but%0a%3c Cruisers will get you better ratios. HCs are great for taking out BBs%0a%3c and above, and as a bonus, they have enough shielding to be effectively%0a%3c immune to Fighters, unless they have CCs behind them. HCs can be%0a%3c included in main battle fleets if you don't mind taking something of a%0a%3c ratio hit.%0a%3c %0a%3c Battleships (BB)%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c The sad fact of AE is that the bigger the ships get, the less efficient%0a%3c they get. Every ship is vulnerable to smaller ships. That holds true for%0a%3c Battleships as well. The efficiency drop from HCs to BBs is huge. Most%0a%3c people have far too many. Still, Battleships have their uses. For taking%0a%3c out Levis and Death Stars, this is the most efficient ship. Battleships%0a%3c are also ''immune'' to Fighters, making them a good ship for taking out%0a%3c weakly defended planets or for holding an occupation. Battleships are%0a%3c poor ships to include in most battle fleets due to their terrible%0a%3c inefficiency against Cruisers/HCs (which is what most enemy fleets are%0a%3c built around).%0a%3c %0a%3c Fleet Carriers (FC)%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Fleet Carriers sacrifice speed for survivability and portage. They have%0a%3c strong enough shields to shield-rape small units. If you have a%0a%3c calculator and you are very careful, it's possible to include FCs in%0a%3c attacks to improve ratios. This is dangerous, though. Don't do it if%0a%3c unless you are experienced. You should have lots of FCs to move all your%0a%3c Fighters around.%0a%3c %0a%3c Dreadnoughts (DN)%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c The bigger you get, the less efficient you get. The big stuff is best%0a%3c used against things that can't hurt it. The strength of these units is%0a%3c their shields. They're great for taking out bases that have defenses%0a%3c weaker than Disruptors, so long as there aren't fleet units big enough%0a%3c to have a chance at taking you down. Dreadnoughts can make a fair%0a%3c addition to a combat fleet if A) you're fighting things that won't be%0a%3c able to kill one, given the dispersion of damage amongst your units and%0a%3c B) you're prepared to slow your entire fleet down in order to include%0a%3c them. If you might lose one, you're better off leaving it out. If you%0a%3c can safely add one without losing it, feel free; it'll soak some damage%0a%3c away from your other units.%0a%3c %0a%3c Titans (TI)%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c This is the first unit with high enough shields to shield-rape Cruisers.%0a%3c That makes them very handy. On the downside, these things are slower%0a%3c than zombies playing Monopoly. HCs will kill them efficiently if you hit%0a%3c them with enough. BBs will kill them less efficiently, but require less%0a%3c bulk. Something like 130 HCs will kill a Titan, tech dependent, but it%0a%3c only takes about 20 BBs. The HCs should get about a 2:1 ratio, while the%0a%3c BBs will get less than 1.5:1.  Titans are great to send out solo to%0a%3c smash bases with less than rings.%0a%3c %0a%3c This guide does not (yet) cover bigger ships. By the time you are able%0a%3c to build them, you should have experience to know how to use them.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Heavy Cruisers (HCs)%0a> ~~~~~~~~%0a> %0a> The only thing HCs can't hurt is a Death Star. HCs are handy against the big stuff, but I don't use them in main fleet formations unless I'm attacking something with BBs or higher. HCs are fairly efficient, but Cruisers will get you better ratios. HCs are great for taking out BBs and above, and as a bonus, they have enough shielding to be effectively immune to fighters, unless they have CCs behind them. HCs can be included in main battle fleets if y